uk.ac.cf.cs.scm5mjw.mda.io
Class Parser

java.lang.Object
  uk.ac.cf.cs.scm5mjw.mda.io.Parser

public final class Parser
extends java.lang.Object

This is a class which handles reading input from a file and converting it into data usable by the simulator. It handles the lexical analysis aspects (converting the input stream to tokens/symbols) and the parsing (using the tokens to generate useful constructs) aspects.

Method Detail

getLineNumber

public int getLineNumber()
An accessor to get the current line number. Line numbering begins at 1.

skipWhitelines

public int skipWhitelines()
This method will skip as many 'whitelines' of immediate input as possible and returns the number of lines skipped. When a line which has non-whitespace characters on it is encountered, that line will NOT be skipped and none of the input on that line will be consumed (even any whitespace starting on that line).

A 'whiteline' is a line containing only whitespace (or just a line on its own).

skipWhitespace

public boolean skipWhitespace()
This method will skip as much whitespace in the immediate input and returns true if whitespace was skipped. If no whitespace was skipped, this will return false.

skipCharacter

public boolean skipCharacter(char c)
This method will skip a single specified character. This will return true if a character was successfully skipped and false otherwise.
The method is written to handle the case that the char has some special meaning in regular expressions. For example, ( has special meaning in a regular expression. If the character is a (, the method will handle this and correctly attempt to skip a literal (.

parseInt

public int parseInt()
This method will parse an integer (and return it) using forthcoming input. Only the integer itself will be consumed. It will NOT ignore whitespace or any other characters -- the integer MUST start in the input immediately. It will not consume any characters that are not part of the integer itself.

Throws:
java.lang.NumberFormatException - if no integer can be found immediately in the input or the integer was not in the expected format of an integer

parseDouble

public double parseDouble()
This method will parse a real number as a double (and return it) using forthcoming input. Only the number itself will be consumed. It will NOT ignore whitespace or any other characters -- the number MUST start in the input immediately. It will not consume any characters that are not part of the number itself.

Throws:
java.lang.NumberFormatException - if no real number can be found immediately in the input or the number was not in the expected format of a real number

parseDoublePoint

public java.awt.geom.Point2D.Double parseDoublePoint()
This will parse a point (x and y coordinates) using forthcoming input.
This will NOT ignore whitespace (or other characters) before or after the point. Similarly, it will NOT consume characters that are not related to the point itself.
A point is composed of two coordinates (numbers) separated by a comma, surrounded by parenthesis. Any amount of whitespace is allowed at the following positions:
- after the (
- before the )
- before or after the comma

Examples are:
(3,4)
( 3,4)
( 3 , 4)
( 3, 4 )

This method will parse points whose coordinate values are real numbers as doubles.

isEOF

public boolean isEOF()
This method will check for end of file by checking if any input is left. This will not consume any input.

parseMap

public static MobilityMap parseMap(java.io.File inFile)
                            throws java.io.FileNotFoundException
This method will interpret a representation of a MobilityMap from a text file, building and returning a MobilityMap object from this representation.
It is a high-level method and makes use of the lexical facilities offered by Parser.

We interpret the adjacency matrix as follows:
A non-zero in entry A[i][j] indicates that the ith node is connected to the jth node.
(where i indicates the row number and j indicates the column number)

To clarify what 'connected to' means:
"node i is connected to node j"
Means that there is an edge going AWAY from node i, and going TOWARDS node j. Thus, FROM node i we can get to node j (but not necessarily the other way around)

For example:
     A    B    C
A    0    0    0
B    0.5  0    0.5
C    0    0    0
This matrix would make a graph with the following links:
- Node B connects to node A
- Node B connects to node C

I have also made the assumption that for the two-dimensional array, the array-of-arrays is the array containing references to ROWS. For example, given a two-dimensional array M, the array given by
M[3]
has all the elements of the row at index 3 (i.e. the fourth row). Thus we have:
M[rowNum][colNum]
For example, in matrix:
a b
c d
'b' is given by M[0][1]

Also, internally we index map nodes from 0. However, it is easier for users to think of indexing from 1 (especially since the mathematical convention is for the rows and columns of adjacency matrixes to index from 1). As such, I adopt the convention that, to the USER, map nodes should index from 1.
This is is not directly relevant to this method (since there is no explicit indexing or reference to nodes when parsing a map), but it is important to bear in mind his convention in other situations.


Note that the sum of weights going from a given node should equal 1. Thus the sum of the values in each row should equal 1.


If the adjacency matrix states that a node is connected to itself, this method will accept this as a valid link and attempt to connect the node to itself (as is permissible in graphs). However, in the case of this system we do not allow a map node to be connected to itself, thus this an error will be raised if an attempt to do so is made.


The following requirements are enforced while parsing the map:
- The map must NOT have any dead ends, i.e. every node must have at least one link going away from it. (thus the sum of every row should be 1)

Throws:
java.io.FileNotFoundException

parseMobileObjectList

public static java.util.Vector<MobileObject> parseMobileObjectList(java.io.File inFile,
                                                                   MobilityMap map)
                                                            throws java.io.FileNotFoundException
This method will interpret a representation of a list of MobileObjects from a text file based on the given map.

At the start of the file the number of list entries must be specified (the number of list entries is not necessarily the number of mobile objects!).

Examples of possible list entries are:
node_index: number_of_mobileobjects; speed
(a number of mobile objects at the given node with a given speed)
node_index: number_of_mobileobjects
(a number of mobile objects at the given node with default speed)


Note that here we assume map nodes index from 1, not 0. (Internally we index map nodes from 0, as in MobilityMap)

Multiple entries may exist for the same node index, thus allowing multiple mobile objects at the same map node to have different speeds.
The destination of mobile objects will be chosen using the weighted random method.

Throws:
java.io.FileNotFoundException

parseInformationSourceList

public static java.util.Vector<InformationSource> parseInformationSourceList(java.io.File inFile)
                                                                      throws java.io.FileNotFoundException
This method will interpret a representation of a list of Information Sources from a text file.

At the start of the file the number of information sources must be specified. Next (after a blankline delimiter) should be a list of information sources (one per line).
The format of an information source should be:
coord: resourceID
For example:
(3,50): 1

Any amount of whitespace is allowed before or after the colon.

Throws:
java.io.FileNotFoundException
